WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.480
We've talked about the three factors of authentication, authentication by knowledge, authentication

00:19.480 --> 00:37.800
by ownership. We've talked about the three factors of authentication, authentication

00:37.800 --> 00:43.960
by knowledge, authentication by ownership, and authentication by characteristic. Let's dig

00:43.960 --> 00:47.760
into the first two, authentication by knowledge, and authentication by ownership.

00:48.000 --> 00:52.720
We're going to start with authentication by knowledge. Authentication by knowledge means

00:52.720 --> 00:57.840
something that you know. So what are some examples of that? Well, things like passwords,

00:57.840 --> 01:04.480
past phrases, security questions, things like that. What's a past phrase, specifically? Well,

01:04.480 --> 01:10.560
a past phrase is meant to be a sentence or a lyric from a song, something that's multiple words

01:10.560 --> 01:15.360
long that you can easily remember. And so the idea behind it is to make a password that's very

01:15.360 --> 01:20.640
long but still easy to remember. So that's a past phrase. And what are security questions? Well,

01:20.640 --> 01:25.520
that's things like, what's your favorite color pumpkin or why do whales smell funny? Things

01:25.520 --> 01:28.800
like that. The questions that you would remember the answers to. Maybe those are good ones.

01:30.160 --> 01:36.160
Now let's talk about authentication by ownership, which is something that you have. One of the most

01:36.160 --> 01:42.720
common types of authentication by ownership is often referred to as OTP or one-time passwords.

01:42.720 --> 01:48.960
These are devices that generate one-time passwords that are only used once. And there's two types

01:48.960 --> 01:56.640
of one-time password generators. There's soft tokens and hard tokens. Software, soft tokens

01:56.640 --> 02:03.120
implies that what's generating the one-time passwords is software. Whereas hard tokens means that

02:03.120 --> 02:08.880
the device that's generating the tokens is a piece of hardware, like an RSA ID key. Let me show

02:08.880 --> 02:14.960
you an example of a soft token. So on my iPhone here, to log into all my super secure accounts and

02:14.960 --> 02:20.480
so forth, I use the Google authenticator. And as you can see, please not log into my accounts. Here are

02:20.480 --> 02:25.200
the one-time passwords that are generated for a bunch of the services that I access. And as you'll

02:25.200 --> 02:30.000
see in a moment here, these passwords will expire and then new ones will be generated. That's why they're

02:30.000 --> 02:37.920
called one-time passwords. The other example of authentication by ownership is things called smart

02:37.920 --> 02:44.080
cards or memory cards. And we'll get into those in a moment. First, let's spend a little more

02:44.080 --> 02:49.680
time on one-time passwords. Because there's actually two ways that we can generate these one-time

02:49.680 --> 02:57.680
passwords, asynchronous and synchronous. So what's the difference? Here's how asynchronous one-time

02:57.680 --> 03:02.560
passwords work. The user will start by saying to the server, I would like to authenticate.

03:02.640 --> 03:09.120
The server will respond back with a challenge. And it's basically just a code. The user will then

03:09.120 --> 03:13.680
have a device. And they have to challenge that or they have to type that challenge into their

03:13.680 --> 03:20.160
device, type that code into their device. When they type that code in, their device will generate

03:20.160 --> 03:25.920
a response through some sort of software mechanism. It'll generate a response and show it on the

03:25.920 --> 03:31.520
screen. The user then has to type that response back into their system. And that response is then

03:31.520 --> 03:38.400
sent back to the server. So asynchronous implies that there's a challenge and then a response back.

03:39.120 --> 03:43.200
And so it's pretty rare to see these. One perfect example of this is they're the Bloomberg

03:43.200 --> 03:47.360
terminal access cards. It's really cool how these work actually. I've seen a couple of them.

03:47.360 --> 03:50.720
So what the way this works is you've got this card. And on the back of the card, there's actually

03:50.720 --> 03:55.200
a little camera. And when the user wants to authenticate to their very expensive Bloomberg terminal,

03:55.200 --> 04:00.960
they actually hold the card up to their screen. And the screen will flash black and white really

04:00.960 --> 04:07.760
quickly. And it's actually sending a code a challenge through the screen to the card. The cards

04:07.760 --> 04:13.440
camera picks that up and then generates the appropriate response. And it shows it on the screen.

04:13.440 --> 04:17.520
The user then has to type in that response along with their other authentication information

04:17.520 --> 04:22.400
in order to get access. So that's an example of a asynchronous system. Pretty rare to see those.

04:23.600 --> 04:29.120
Now what about synchronous systems? The reason we call these synchronous is because the device

04:29.120 --> 04:34.720
and the server are in sync. They're generating the same one-time password every 30 seconds or

04:34.720 --> 04:40.480
60 seconds, whatever it happens to be. So how do synchronous devices work? Well, it would be just

04:40.480 --> 04:45.120
like what I showed you on my phone here or an RSA ID key. You've got a device either a soft token

04:45.120 --> 04:52.800
or a hard token that's generating a one-time password all the time. And whenever you want to log in,

04:52.800 --> 04:57.200
you simply read the one-time password off your device, type into the computer system,

04:57.200 --> 05:03.520
and send that to the server. The server is in sync with the device. It's generating the same

05:03.520 --> 05:07.680
one-time password at the same time. And so if the one-time password that you type in is the same

05:07.680 --> 05:11.360
one that it's generated for this period of time, then it will authenticate you.

05:13.520 --> 05:18.320
Now let's talk about smart cards and memory cards. And actually, a perfect way to talk about this

05:18.320 --> 05:22.640
is by looking at a credit, a modern day credit card. Because it's both a smart card and a memory

05:22.640 --> 05:25.920
card. And by the way, this is my real credit card. So I've blacked it out. Please don't

05:26.080 --> 05:32.560
steal my card. Now, how does a modern day credit card demonstrate both smart card and memory card?

05:32.560 --> 05:38.400
Let's start with a simple aspect, memory card. And memory card implies that it's just some memory,

05:38.400 --> 05:42.080
just some data that's stored. And if you look on the back of the credit card, and I'm intentionally

05:42.080 --> 05:46.000
covering up my CVV number here, if you look on the back of my credit card, there's a magnetic strip

05:46.000 --> 05:51.520
here. That magnetic strip just contains some data, some memory. So when you swipe this card through

05:51.520 --> 05:57.760
a reader, it would read that memory and then generate and that data that's read off of the memory

05:57.760 --> 06:02.880
area is what would allow your credit card transaction to go through. And this is what made older style

06:02.880 --> 06:07.360
credit cards so incredibly easy to copy because all you have to do is exactly copy this data,

06:07.360 --> 06:10.880
and as long as you use that data off of there, you could make a credit card payment.

06:11.680 --> 06:16.640
Modern credit cards don't use just memory. They are actually smart cards. So if you look at this

06:16.640 --> 06:21.120
little piece right here on my credit card, this is actually a little computer chip underneath here.

06:21.840 --> 06:26.400
And this is where we have to talk about, there's two types of smart cards that are under known as

06:26.400 --> 06:32.480
contact and contact lists. So contact implies that when you put this card into a reader,

06:32.480 --> 06:37.840
this chip area here has to actually make contact with the reader. And it's through these metal

06:37.840 --> 06:43.440
contacts here that the chip is actually powered. And the way this works in smart cards is that

06:43.440 --> 06:48.320
when you plug the card in to a reader, there's a bit of communication that goes back and forth between

06:48.480 --> 06:53.840
the card and the reader to process the credit card transaction. And what's important about this is

06:53.840 --> 06:59.040
that the numbers that come off of this card are unique every time. So you can't just copy the data

06:59.040 --> 07:04.240
off of here and make a copy of the credit card. It's more intelligent than that. So that's contact.

07:04.240 --> 07:09.760
It's the same underlying concept of a smart card in that with contact lists, there's a little radio

07:09.760 --> 07:14.320
receivaring here. And when you get this near to a reader, the reader is constantly sending out

07:14.320 --> 07:20.400
strong pulses. And that pulse will be read by the card. And importantly, that pulse is powerful

07:20.400 --> 07:25.760
enough to actually power the card in here or to power the little chip in here for a moment so

07:25.760 --> 07:31.040
that it can perform some calculations and then send a signal back to the reader. So all of this is

07:31.040 --> 07:37.200
actually powered by pulses being sent out by the reader, powers the chip, comes up with a number,

07:37.200 --> 07:43.600
responds back to the reader, and that's how contact lists works. Both examples, contact and contact

07:43.600 --> 07:58.560
lists of smart cards, which is a method of authentication by ownership.

